texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>,</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>right triangle</b> or <b>right-angled triangle</b>, sometimes calle=
d an <b>orthogonal triangle</b> or <b>rectangular triangle</b>, is a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle" title=3D"Triangle">triangle</a=
> in which two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edge_(geometry)" ti=
tle=3D"Edge (geometry)">sides</a> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpendicular">perpendicular</a>, forming a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_angle" title=3D"Right angle">ri=
ght angle</a> (<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<s=
pan class=3D"den">4</span></span> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Turn_(unit)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Turn (unit)">turn</a> or 90 <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degree_(angle)" title=3D"Degree (angl=
e)">degrees</a>).
</p><p>The side opposite to the right angle is called the <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypotenuse" title=3D"Hypotenuse">hypotenuse</a><=
/i> (side <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span cl=
ass=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;=
"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displayst=
yle c}">
