</p><p>Every right triangle is half of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Rectangle" title=3D"Rectangle">rectangle</a> which has been divided =
along its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diagonal" title=3D"Diago=
nal">diagonal</a>. When the rectangle is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Square" title=3D"Square">square</a>, its right-triangular half is =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isosceles_triangle" title=3D"Isosc=
eles triangle">isosceles</a>, with two congruent sides and two congruent an=
gles. When the rectangle is not a square, its right-triangular half is <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalene_triangle" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Scalene triangle">scalene</a>.
</p><p>Every triangle whose <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_(=
geometry)" title=3D"Base (geometry)">base</a> is the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Diameter" title=3D"Diameter">diameter</a> of a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circle</a> and w=
hose <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apex_(geometry)" title=3D"Ape=
x (geometry)">apex</a> lies on the circle is a right triangle, with the rig=
ht angle at the apex and the hypotenuse as the base; conversely, the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circumcircle" title=3D"Circumcircle">cir=
cumcircle</a> of any right triangle has the hypotenuse as its diameter. Thi=
s is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thales%27_theorem" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Thales' theorem">Thales' theorem</a>.
</p><p>The legs and hypotenuse of a right triangle satisfy the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem" title=3D"Pythagorean theo=
rem">Pythagorean theorem</a>: the sum of the areas of the squares on two le=
gs is the area of the square on the hypotenuse, <span class=3D"mwe-math-ele=
ment mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-mat=
h-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/19=
98/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle a^{2}+b^{2}=3Dc^{2}.}">
