span> of a right triangle</figcaption></figure>
<p>If an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Altitude_(triangle)" titl=
e=3D"Altitude (triangle)">altitude</a> is drawn from the vertex, with the r=
ight angle to the hypotenuse, then the triangle is divided into two smaller=
 triangles; these are both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Similar=
ity_(geometry)" title=3D"Similarity (geometry)">similar</a> to the original=
, and therefore similar to each other. From this:
</p>
<ul><li>The altitude to the hypotenuse is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Geometric_mean" title=3D"Geometric mean">geometric mean</a> (<a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ratio#Euclid's_definitions" title=3D=
"Ratio">mean proportional</a>) of the two segments of the hypotenuse.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Posamentier_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Right_triangle#cite_note-Posamentier-2"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup cla=
ss=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 243">:=E2=80=8A243=
=E2=80=8A</span></sup></li>
<li>Each leg of the triangle is the mean proportional of the hypotenuse and=
 the segment of the hypotenuse that is adjacent to the leg.</li></ul>
<p>In equations,
