        <mi>A</mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle A.}</annotati=
on>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/8a71bf21ad35b8fe05555041d54d1e17eeb0f490" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:2.39ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle A.}"=
></span> The converse states that the hypotenuse of a right triangle is the=
 diameter of its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circumcircle" tit=
le=3D"Circumcircle">circumcircle</a>. As a corollary, the circumcircle has =
its center at the midpoint of the diameter, so the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Median_(geometry)" title=3D"Median (geometry)">median</a> =
through the right-angled vertex is a radius, and the circumradius is half t=
he length of the hypotenuse.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Medians">Medians</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRight_triangle&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Medians"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The following formulas hold for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Median_(geometry)" title=3D"Median (geometry)">medians</a> of a right =
triangle:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e m_{a}^{2}+m_{b}^{2}=3D5m_{c}^{2}=3D{\frac {5}{4}}c^{2}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
