>
<p>In a right triangle, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_=
line" title=3D"Euler line">Euler line</a> contains the median on the hypote=
nuse=E2=80=94that is, it goes through both the right-angled vertex and the =
midpoint of the side opposite that vertex. This is because the right triang=
le's orthocenter, the intersection of its altitudes, falls on the right-ang=
led vertex while its circumcenter, the intersection of its <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection#Perpendicular_bisectors" title=3D"Bisect=
ion">perpendicular bisectors of sides</a>, falls on the midpoint of the hyp=
otenuse.
</p>
